<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06075028 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06075028 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  A coal strike widened Thursday to about 140 mines across the Soviet Union, andsome miners began a hunger strike to draw attention to their demands, whichinclude President Mikhail Gorbachev's resignation. A plunge in coal productionsince the strike began March 1 forced blast furnaces to shut down at fivesteel plants in the Ukraine. Moscow residents collected food to send tostrikers in the Kuznetsk Coal Basin of western Siberia, the nation'ssecond-biggest coal producing region.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  COAL STRIKE EXPANDS IN SOVIET UNION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910315  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  20A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  83  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 15, 199100075028,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>